===Etymology===
{{PIE root|en|bʰeh₂|id=speak}}
From {{etyl|enm|en}}, from {{der|en|fro|fable}}, from {{der|en|la|fabula}}, from {{m|la|fari|fā(rī)|to speak, say}} + {{m|la|-bula||instrumental suffix}}. See {{m|en|Ban}}, and compare {{m|en|fabulous}}, {{m|en|fame}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈfeɪbəl/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-fable.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|eɪbəl|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[fictitious]] [[narrative]] intended to [[enforce]] some useful [[truth]] or [[precept]], usually with [[animals]], etc. as [[characters]]; an [[apologue]]. Prototypically, [[w:Aesop's Fables|Aesop's Fables]].
#: {{syn|en|morality play}}
# Any story told to excite wonder; common talk; the [[theme]] of talk.
#* [[w:First Epistle to Timothy|1 Timothy]] 4:7,
#*: Old wives' '''fables'''.
#* {{quote-book|author=[[w:Alfred Tennyson, 1st Baron Tennyson|Alfred Tennyson]]|passage=We grew / The '''fable''' of the city where we dwelt.}}
#: {{syn|en|legend}}
# [[fiction|Fiction]]; [[untruth]]; falsehood.
#* {{quote-book|author=[[w:Joseph Addison|Joseph Addison]]|passage=It would look like a '''fable''' to report that this gentleman gives away a great fortune by secret methods.}}
# The plot, story, or connected series of events forming the subject of an epic or dramatic poem.
#* {{quote-book|author=Dryden|passage=The moral is the first business of the poet; this being formed, he contrives such a design or '''fable''' as may be most suitable to the moral.}}

